        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided filing chunks, here is a detailed breakdown of what the company discloses about its AI segment revenue, subscriptions, advertising, and the monetization of AI features.\n\n### 1. Segment Reporting and Revenue Breakdowns\nThe company operates three distinct segments: Space, Connectivity, and **AI**. The AI segment operates a vertically integrated platform spanning the Grok frontier model, AI solutions for consumer/enterprise customers, and the X platform. \n\nThe AI segment generates revenue from two primary categories:\n*   **Advertising Revenue:** Generated from the sale of ad products displayed on the X platform.\n*   **AI Solutions and Infrastructure Revenue:** Comprising (i) subscription offerings (X and Grok), (ii) data licensing arrangements, and (iii) API access to Grok models.\n\n**Recent Financial Performance & Drivers:**\n*   **Full Year 2025:** AI segment revenue increased by $581 million (22.2%) compared to 2024. This was driven by a $116 million increase in advertising revenue and a $465 million increase in AI solutions and infrastructure revenue (specifically $365 million from X and Grok subscriptions and $88 million from data licensing).\n*   **Q1 2026 (Three months ended March 31, 2026):** AI segment revenue increased by $91 million (12.5%). AI solutions and infrastructure revenue grew by $191 million (driven by $177 million in Grok and X subscription revenue and $12 million in data licensing). However, this was partially offset by a $100 million decrease in advertising revenue due to a short-term ad platform overhaul.\n*   **Full Year 2024:** AI revenue increased by $254 million, driven by X subscription revenue (+$157 million) and data licensing (+$90 million), offsetting a $595 million drop in advertising revenue from lost ad partners. \n\n### 2. Revenue Recognition Policies\nThe filing explicitly outlines how the AI segment recognizes revenue:\n*   **Advertising:** Recognized in the period the ad is delivered, evidenced by a user engaging with the ad in a manner satisfying the advertiser\'s criteria. The company acts as the principal and recognizes revenue grossly for ads sold directly on X. Ad contracts are typically short-term and cancellable. \n*   **Premium Subscriptions (X and Grok):** Recognized ratably over the subscription term, which ranges from month-to-month up to one year.\n*   **Data Licensing:** Recognized ratably over the period (month-to-month up to two years) as the customer consumes and benefits from the licensed data.\n*   **Grok API Access:** Recognized ratably over the contract term (month-to-month to one year) for stand-ready access, or as services are consumed for usage-based arrangements.\n\n### 3. AI Subscriptions (Grok & X Premium Revenue)\nThe company is heavily focused on converting free users into paid subscribers across its integrated Grok and X platforms. \n*   **Subscriber Base:** As of March 31, 2026, the company reached approximately **6.3 million active paid subscribers**. This consists of roughly **4.4 million X Premium and Premium+ subscribers** and **1.9 million SuperGrok, SuperGrok Heavy, and SuperGrok Lite subscribers**.\n*   **Value Proposition:** Subscribers gain enhanced functionality, exclusive features, and access to the latest Grok AI models. The company believes its exceptional "model velocity" (rapidly developing leading frontier models like the upcoming multi-trillion parameter Grok 5) strengthens the value proposition and supports long-term subscriber growth.\n*   **Market Opportunity:** The company estimates the consumer AI subscription market opportunity at $760 billion, based on a global population of 5.5 billion people aged 10+ and a weighted average monthly subscription revenue of $12 (ranging from $30 in high-income countries to significantly lower in low-income countries).\n\n### 4. Advertising Revenue & AI Integration\nAdvertising remains a core monetization channel for the AI segment, and AI features are being deeply integrated to drive ad performance:\n*   **AI-Driven Advertising:** Grok increasingly supports the advertising strategy by helping advertisers with campaign creation, creative optimization, and alignment with trending topics and user intent. The goal is to make ads feel like content—contextually relevant and integrated into real-time conversations.\n*   **Targeting and Measurement:** The company aims to grow advertising revenue per user by strengthening performance advertising and expanding AI-driven targeting and measurement tools.\n*   **Future Ad Monetization:** The company notes there may be an incremental monetization opportunity by introducing advertising into its stand-alone Grok offering. \n*   **Seasonality:** Advertising revenue experiences seasonality, peaking in Q4 due to end-of-year spending and hitting its lowest point in Q1.\n\n### 5. Broader AI Monetization & Business Model Integration\nBeyond consumer subscriptions and ads, the company monetizes AI through enterprise and infrastructure channels:\n*   **Enterprise and Government Deployments:** The company offers tailored deployments of Grok (Grok Business and Grok Enterprise) customized to specific workflows and security needs. These are sold on **license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing models**.\n*   **Everything App Strategy:** The company is evolving X into an "Everything App" (incorporating payments, banking, commerce, etc. via products like X Money and X Chat). Grok is being embedded throughout the platform to enhance discovery, post analysis, user support, and personalization, which is intended to reduce friction for users to adopt paid features.\n*   **Cost of Revenue & R&D Context:** The AI segment’s cost of revenue includes infrastructure, revenue share, payment processor fees, and creator payments. R&D expenses are heavily tied to training Grok and data center expansions (including GPU hardware depreciation and cloud computing). The company expects AI cost of revenue to decrease as a percentage of revenue over time as it scales and monetizes these offerings.\n\n*(Note: As mentioned in the prompt\'s context, the filing also briefly notes that the company expects marketing spend to decrease as a percentage of revenue over time, and mentions a connectivity impairment related to the discontinuation of a Starlink product line, though these are outside the AI segment.)*',
        error=None,
