    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# User Metrics, MAU Disclosure, and Monetization Framework\n\n## 1. Disclosure of User Metrics\n\nThe filing discloses a layered set of user metrics rather than a single headline number:\n\n- **Supported accounts**: Over 1.3 billion accounts active in the trailing twelve months ended March 31, 2026 (up from over 1.1 billion as of December 31, 2025).\n- **Monthly Active Users (MAUs)**: Approximately 550 million as of March 31, 2026 (up from approximately 520 million at year-end 2025).\n- **Grok AI feature users**: A subset of approximately 117 million MAUs that used Grok\'s AI features as of March 31, 2026.\n- **Paid subscribers**: Approximately 6.3 million active paid subscribers as of March 31, 2026, split between ~4.4 million X Premium/Premium+ subscribers and ~1.9 million SuperGrok (including Heavy and Lite) subscribers.\n\nThe MAU definition is carefully constructed: it counts users who interacted with Grok or X via web browsers or mobile apps at least once in the preceding 30-day period, includes only registered account holders, and attempts to de-duplicate users who access both platforms via sign-in traffic. The company candidly acknowledges that its methodology "may not fully capture all instances of duplication, and our reported MAU should be viewed as an estimate of unique users across our Grok and X platforms for the applicable period." The subset of AI-feature users is tracked "based on the source of their server requests."\n\n## 2. Why MAU Is Disclosed Rather Than Standalone AI Customer Counts\n\nThe filing is explicit that MAU is treated as a supplementary engagement indicator, not a management target. The key passage states:\n\n> "While MAUs provide an estimated measure of the size and engagement of our user base, we are focused on revenue and operating margin, and manage our business with the objective of driving sustainable revenue growth and profitability rather than with the primary objective of growing or maintaining MAU levels."\n\nSeveral reasons emerge from the filing for why the company prefers combined MAU over a standalone AI customer count:\n\n- **Integrated platform thesis**: The company frames Grok and X as an "integrated AI platform," so it presents combined MAUs to convey total reach across both surfaces rather than isolating AI-specific usage.\n- **Revenue-first philosophy**: Management explicitly de-prioritizes top-of-funnel user metrics in favor of financial outcomes. This mirrors the company\'s Starlink ARPU philosophy, where it states its strategy is "focused on driving sustainable revenue growth and expanding our margins through operational efficiencies and technological advancements, rather than prioritizing increases in ARPU."\n- **CODM evaluation framework**: The Chief Operating Decision Maker "assesses performance and allocates resources to operating segments based on segment income (loss) from operations" and "does not evaluate operating and reportable segments using" non-financial user metrics as primary measures.\n- **Volatility of AI app metrics**: The risk factors note that "download and other usage metrics for any individual AI application, including Grok, can fluctuate significantly (including periods of decreased Grok app downloads and user activity) in response to competitor model releases, product update cycles, and broader shifts in user behavior." This volatility makes standalone AI customer counts a less reliable management KPI.\n\nThe 117 million Grok AI-feature MAU figure is disclosed as a subset of the combined MAU base, giving investors visibility into AI adoption without elevating it to the primary metric.\n\n## 3. Relationship Between User Engagement and Monetization\n\nThe filing frames engagement and monetization as tightly coupled but channeled through multiple complementary streams:\n\n### Advertising as the Core Engagement-to-Revenue Engine\n\n- "We also monetize user activity through high-impact advertising inventory on X."\n- X\'s "scale, real-time engagement, and integration with Grok provide a differentiated foundation for building a unified user experience across communication, content discovery, commerce, and financial services."\n- The company aims to "grow advertising revenue per user by strengthening performance advertising, expanding AI-driven targeting and measurement, and introducing richer ad formats and creative tools."\n- A "central focus" is "making ads feel like content—contextually relevant, aligned with user interests, and integrated into real-time conversations."\n- Grok supports advertising by "helping advertisers with campaign creation, creative optimization, and alignment with trending topics and user intent."\n- The April 2026 rollout of the rebuilt X Ads Manager is designed to enable "more precise, relevant, and dynamic ad delivery" with AI-powered systems.\n- Advertising revenue is recognized "in the period when advertising is delivered as evidenced by a person engaging with an ad on the Company\'s platforms in a manner satisfying the types of engagement selected by the advertisers"—directly tying revenue recognition to user engagement events.\n\n### Enterprise AI Deployments\n\nFor enterprises, the company offers "tailored deployments of Grok customized to specific workflows and security needs through Grok Business and Grok Enterprise, sold on license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing models." This creates a monetization path beyond consumer advertising, where enterprise value is derived from the same underlying AI capabilities.\n\n### Risk Linkage Between Engagement and Revenue\n\nThe risk factors make the engagement-monetization linkage explicit in the downward direction:\n\n> "If users do not continue to contribute content and otherwise engage with the X platform, we are unable to provide users with valuable and timely content, or if content that is considered to be problematic or offensive is made available on the X platform, the size of the X platform\'s user base and their engagement may decline, leading to a decline in monetizable usage and the loss of potential subscription revenue from such users."\n\nA decline in X users could also "impact the ongoing development of our AI product, which in part utilizes data and user-generated content from the X platform," creating a compounding negative feedback loop.\n\n## 4. Conversion of Free Users to Paid Subscribers\n\nThe filing dedicates a specific subsection to this topic:\n\n> "Conversion of Users to Paid Subscribers. In parallel, we are focused on converting a greater portion of our user base into paying subscribers through our X subscription (Premium and Premium+) and Grok subscription offerings. Subscribers benefit from enhanced functionality, exclusive features, and access to our latest AI models."\n\nThe conversion strategy rests on several pillars:\n\n- **Feature differentiation**: Premium tiers offer "enhanced functionality, exclusive features, and access to our latest AI models."\n- **Model velocity as a conversion driver**: The company emphasizes that "our AI segment has demonstrated exceptional model velocity: since launching Grok, we have developed leading frontier models at a far faster rate of innovation than others," and it plans to "continue adding new features and functionality while releasing increasingly capable Grok models to increase the penetration rate of our subscriber base."\n- **Scale of opportunity**: With 550 million MAUs and only 6.3 million paid subscribers, the implied penetration rate is roughly 1.1%, which the company frames as a large upside opportunity.\n- **Multiple subscription tiers**: The existence of SuperGrok, SuperGrok Heavy, and SuperGrok Lite alongside X Premium and Premium+ suggests a tiered pricing strategy designed to capture different willingness-to-pay segments.\n\n## 5. Capital Allocation Strategy\n\nThe filing introduces a section titled "Our Capital Allocation and Funding Strategy," signaling a formal framework. While the detailed content of this section is not fully captured in the provided excerpts, the surrounding context indicates that capital allocation is tied to:\n\n- Massive infrastructure investment, including the goal of launching "100 gigawatts of compute to space each year."\n- The Terafab AI chip manufacturing initiative designed to "vertically integrate the design, fabrication, and deployment of advanced logic and memory chips."\n- Strategic collaborations with Tesla on processors and the Macrohard agentic AI platform.\n- Risk factor acknowledgment that capital expenditure decisions may need modification "in response to technological change, competitive pressures, regulatory developments or commercial adoption trends."\n\n## Summary\n\nThe filing presents a coherent philosophy: MAU is disclosed as an engagement indicator but explicitly subordinated to revenue and operating margin as management objectives. The company avoids standalone AI customer counts in favor of combined platform MAU with an AI-feature subset, reflecting both its integrated platform thesis and the inherent volatility of AI app usage metrics. Monetization flows from engagement through three channels—advertising (where revenue recognition is literally triggered by user engagement events), enterprise AI deployments with flexible pricing models, and subscription conversions—each reinforced by Grok\'s AI capabilities. The conversion strategy leverages model velocity and feature exclusivity to drive a currently low (~1.1%) paid penetration rate higher, while the capital allocation framework directs resources toward compute infrastructure and vertical integration designed to lower token costs over time.',
